punished for...
Shamed.

17:54.274 --> 17:56.008
- Shamed for reading...
- Yes.

17:56.042 --> 17:58.278
For having an education,
for aspiring to those things.

17:58.311 --> 18:01.381
Yeah, you saw
a decline in education

18:01.414 --> 18:03.650
that continued for 30 years.

18:03.683 --> 18:05.718
The biggest obstacle
in this country

18:05.752 --> 18:07.520
is the political class.

18:07.554 --> 18:09.456
Because what we've had,
you know, in Nigeria is

18:09.489 --> 18:12.125
if you lose elections,
you then jump to the other party

18:12.159 --> 18:13.793
and you win elections,

18:13.826 --> 18:15.995
and then if you lose,
you go back to this other party.

18:16.028 --> 18:17.323
- Right.
- So it's the same people.

18:17.330 --> 18:19.499
They're going to fight
tooth and nail

18:19.532 --> 18:20.800
to stay in office

18:20.833 --> 18:22.969
and to keep the system
the way it is.

18:26.005 --> 18:28.475
♪

18:28.508 --> 18:30.877
Pepper soup
is the food of the night

18:30.910 --> 18:33.646
in dark places.

18:33.680 --> 18:35.047
It burns,

18:35.081 --> 18:36.816
it burns real good.

18:36.849 --> 18:38.151
Delicious.

18:38.185 --> 18:40.720
This is a very IT savvy country.

18:40.753 --> 18:43.990
Nigerian Internet scammers
are world-renowned.

18:44.023 --> 18:46.359
They are a tiny minority,
I must tell you.

18:46.393 --> 18:48.261
It may not be
a legitimate enterprise,

18:48.295 --> 18:51.398
but you've got some very smart,
hardworking people.

18:51.431 --> 18:52.932
They're very talented.

18:52.965 --> 18:55.235
Imagine if they were
all well-educated,

18:55.268 --> 18:57.337
if they had access to finance.

18:57.370 --> 18:59.572
I believe if
you're a black person,

18:59.606 --> 19:02.275
whether you're African
or you're African-American,

19:02.309 --> 19:04.577
you're never going to
get any respect

19:04.611 --> 19:08.948
unless there's a successful
black nation.

19:08.981 --> 19:12.219
♪

19:12.252 --> 19:13.653
It is unwise
to hold other people,

19:13.686 --> 19:16.155
your employer,
or even the government

19:16.189 --> 19:17.924
accountable for your success.

19:17.957 --> 19:21.160
That is the only way people
are going to respect you.

19:21.194 --> 19:22.262
You must do it...

19:22.295 --> 19:23.763
Yourself.

19:26.799 --> 19:29.769
♪

19:40.513 --> 19:43.816
Queen Elizabeth
came to Nigeria in 1959.

19:43.850 --> 19:45.485
The 33 million people

19:45.518 --> 19:47.454
of England's most prosperous
African colony

19:47.487 --> 19:49.222
were ready for independence.

19:49.256 --> 19:52.925
♪

19:52.959 --> 19:55.061
A friend of mine sends me
a text, and it says,

19:55.094 --> 19:58.097
"Are you aware of
Nigerian psych rock

19:58.130 --> 19:59.399
of the '70s?"
Yes.

19:59.432 --> 20:01.268
There was a war in the late '60s

20:01.301 --> 20:03.936
and that caused
a whole shift in the sound,

20:03.970 --> 20:05.972
because before the war
was high life.

20:06.005 --> 20:08.675
♪

20:08.708 --> 20:13.246
And after the war, it was rock
and all sorts of sounds.

20:16.283 --> 20:16.783
♪

20:24.957 --> 20:28.495
This is mind-blowing,
like, amazing stuff.

20:28.528 --> 20:30.196
This was...
This was a game changer.

20:30.229 --> 20:32.399
♪

20:32.432 --> 20:35.268
It's as if everybody took acid
at the same time.

20:35.302 --> 20:37.069
It was less the acid

20:37.103 --> 20:40.039
and more, let's just freak out.

20:40.072 --> 20:43.109
♪

20:43.142 --> 20:46.779
These new sounds, mutations
on funk, jazz, and rock,

20:46.813 --> 20:50.082
marked an explosive change
in Nigerian culture.

20:50.116 --> 20:52.018
♪

20:52.051 --> 20:53.846
How'd it do when it came out?
It was wildfire.

20:53.853 --> 20:55.288
It was a hit.
Really?

20:55.322 --> 20:56.923
It was a hit.
It was a massive hit.

20:56.956 --> 21:00.560
Kemi Castro is a collector
and aficionado.

21:00.593 --> 21:01.093
♪

21:06.733 --> 21:08.868
This is really where
it started from.

21:08.901 --> 21:10.503
- Uh-huh.
- Blo.

21:10.537 --> 21:12.131
They had a very trippy song,
which I'll play for you.

21:12.138 --> 21:13.306
Yeah, let's hear it.

21:16.343 --> 21:16.843
♪

21:22.014 --> 21:24.083
This is... freaky.

21:24.116 --> 21:27.219
♪

21:31.691 --> 21:34.494
♪

21:34.527 --> 21:37.964
That shift in music
had to do a lot with the war.

21:37.997 --> 21:41.401
♪

21:41.434 --> 21:43.135
Nigeria's rebel eastern state,

21:43.169 --> 21:45.605
the Republic of Biafra,
declared its independence.

21:45.638 --> 21:48.608
♪

21:48.641 --> 21:51.844
That music was needed to
translate the darkness.

21:51.878 --> 21:54.080
Soldiers of
the breakaway province

21:54.113 --> 21:56.616
suffered heavy casualties
and ultimate defeat.

21:56.649 --> 21:59.586
A thousand Biafrans a day
died of starvation.

21:59.619 --> 22:02.922
The music was a defiant
middle finger to war...

22:02.955 --> 22:06.192
to corruption,
and repressive military rule.

22:06.225 --> 22:07.560
You know how military dictators

22:07.594 --> 22:09.295
try and control everything.

22:09.328 --> 22:11.063
But of all the music
of the time,

22:11.097 --> 22:13.766
nothing and nobody took it
directly to the people

22:13.800 --> 22:16.836
in such explicitly
confrontational terms

22:16.869 --> 22:20.707
as Afrobeat and its architect,
Fela Kuti.

22:20.740 --> 22:23.242
The government were
giving Fela a hard time

22:23.275 --> 22:24.677
because he was protesting
by name...

22:24.711 --> 22:26.613
- Yeah.
- Specific things.

22:26.646 --> 22:29.716
I mean, they identified him
as a existential threat,

22:29.749 --> 22:30.850
and he was.

22:32.318 --> 22:33.753
People would show up
at the Shrine.

22:33.786 --> 22:35.354
- Exactly.
- Like, what's he gonna say?

22:35.388 --> 22:37.056
What's he mad about today?

22:41.193 --> 22:43.229
Fela was an African superstar,

22:43.262 --> 22:47.066
a loud, persistent, and
unwavering voice of opposition

22:47.099 --> 22:48.935
and resistance.

22:48.968 --> 22:51.337
♪ Zombie no go, go
unless you tell him to go ♪

22:51.370 --> 22:53.239
♪ Zombie

22:53.272 --> 22:56.008
♪ Zombie no go stop
unless you tell him to stop ♪

22:56.042 --> 22:58.144
People protested
but they didn't name names.

22:58.177 --> 22:59.812
- Right.
- But Fela would name names

22:59.846 --> 23:02.048
and... and say, you know,
you're a... thief.

23:02.081 --> 23:05.151
♪

23:08.688 --> 23:10.723
♪

23:13.826 --> 23:14.326
♪

23:22.168 --> 23:23.636
♪ Uh-huh

23:23.670 --> 23:26.138
♪ Quick march slow march ♪

23:26.172 --> 23:27.507
♪ Left turn right turn

23:27.540 --> 23:29.308
♪ About turn double up

23:29.341 --> 23:31.210
♪ Salute open your hat

23:31.243 --> 23:32.912
♪ Stand at ease fall in

23:32.945 --> 23:36.248
♪ Fall out fall down get ready ♪

23:45.157 --> 23:48.294
For one decade, Fela's voice
was the only voice here

23:48.327 --> 23:50.162
opposing the dictators.

23:50.196 --> 23:52.264
And he paid a very high price.

23:52.298 --> 23:54.767
His house was burned.
He was stopped from playing.

23:54.801 --> 23:57.804
Fela died in 1997 of AIDS

23:57.837 --> 24:00.473
after a social life that could
be best described

24:00.507 --> 24:02.208
as complicated.

24:02.241 --> 24:05.645
He married 27 wives
in one day, for instance,

24:05.678 --> 24:09.015
but he left behind an enormous
legacy and a family,

24:09.048 --> 24:12.284
including two internationally
celebrated musicians

24:12.318 --> 24:13.385
in their own right,

24:13.419 --> 24:15.855
Femi and Seun Kuti.

24:24.764 --> 24:25.264
♪

24:34.240 --> 24:35.842
Because of Fela,

24:35.875 --> 24:39.912
we are able to voice
our opinions today.

24:39.946 --> 24:43.550
If things are not right,
you can't just gloss over it.

24:43.583 --> 24:45.818
There is no reason why
this country

24:45.852 --> 24:47.820
cannot be ten times better.

24:47.854 --> 24:49.522
Daughter Yeni runs this place,

24:49.556 --> 24:51.390
the New Afrika Shrine...

24:51.423 --> 24:53.192
We have more money,
we have more oil,

24:53.225 --> 24:54.861
but we have bad leaders.

24:54.894 --> 24:57.797
Both a musical venue
and political pulpit

24:57.830 --> 25:01.133
with a vital position at the
epicenter of Nigerian music.

25:01.167 --> 25:01.667
♪

25:11.010 --> 25:11.510
♪

25:20.519 --> 25:21.921
So you drink beer.

25:21.954 --> 25:23.723
If Anthony is drinking beer,

25:23.756 --> 25:25.625
I'm drinking beer, too.
How can you say

25:25.658 --> 25:27.452
because he's drinking beer,
you're drinking beer?

25:27.459 --> 25:29.128
- I'm a fan.
- Of him drinking beer?

25:29.161 --> 25:31.330
No, of him.
No, I'm a fan of beer, too,

25:31.363 --> 25:34.066
but you know, he's drinking
beer, I'm drinking beer.

25:35.602 --> 25:37.570
You grew up at
your dad's compound,

25:37.604 --> 25:39.005
and I know at one point,

25:39.038 --> 25:41.173
he wanted you to become
an area boy.

25:41.207 --> 25:43.743
He thought that
that would be good street cred.

25:43.776 --> 25:46.245
That's to put it kind of mild.

25:46.278 --> 25:48.781
He just wanted me to be...

25:48.815 --> 25:50.617
like, from the streets.

25:50.650 --> 25:53.485
We've been running into
area boys constantly

25:53.519 --> 25:55.487
through this week,
and I kinda want to know

25:55.521 --> 25:57.156
how the structure works, like...

25:57.189 --> 25:59.018
If you wanted to go for
elections, for instance,

25:59.025 --> 26:02.061
you needed... you'll need to see
all the area boys.

26:02.094 --> 26:03.963
You'll have to give
a lot of money

26:03.996 --> 26:07.600
for him to get all his
gang members to vote for you.

26:07.634 --> 26:11.070
And if you do a good job
in dealing with this,

26:11.103 --> 26:12.672
you probably would win.

26:12.705 --> 26:15.107
That's not quite democracy,
though, is it?

26:15.141 --> 26:16.809
No, it's not.

26:16.843 --> 26:19.511
Nigeria is not really,
you know, a democratic state.

26:22.548 --> 26:23.048
♪

26:26.619 --> 26:28.487
♪ Struggle music

26:28.520 --> 26:30.456
♪ Struggle sounds

26:30.489 --> 26:32.258
♪ Struggle people

26:32.291 --> 26:34.426
♪ Struggling now

26:34.460 --> 26:36.362
♪ Struggle music
struggle sounds ♪

26:36.395 --> 26:37.997
♪ Struggle people struggle now

26:38.030 --> 26:40.967
♪ Struggle music
struggle sounds ♪

26:41.000 --> 26:42.468
♪

26:42.501 --> 26:44.336
What is going on
in Africa today for me,

26:44.370 --> 26:46.105
I think, is a perverse
kind of hopelessness,

26:46.138 --> 26:48.240
working for a system
that is oppressing you,

26:48.274 --> 26:50.169
and you know they're oppressing
you but you've given up that

26:50.176 --> 26:51.811
there's nothing
I can do about it.

26:51.844 --> 26:53.646
I mean, is that what you see?

26:53.680 --> 26:55.247
Because honestly...
Yeah.

26:55.281 --> 26:57.009
I've never been in a country
where everybody was

26:57.016 --> 26:58.918
working so hard at something.

26:58.951 --> 27:00.519
- They're hustling.
- They're hustling.

27:00.552 --> 27:02.221
Look, I've been to the DRC,

27:02.254 --> 27:05.324
to Goma and Kisangani, and those
were not hopeful places.

27:05.357 --> 27:07.894
Yeah, but... but Nigeria
is the same way as DRC

27:07.927 --> 27:10.963
and the North are because we
have the Boko Haram insurgency.

27:10.997 --> 27:13.632
People are being killed, but
nobody wants to talk about it.

27:13.666 --> 27:16.035
Nobody wants to act as if it's
as serious as...

27:16.068 --> 27:18.404
Because Nigeria, we play...
We play the game.

27:18.437 --> 27:19.638
We are the kings of the game.

27:19.672 --> 27:21.440
We were so proud

27:21.473 --> 27:23.368
when Nigeria arrived in Kenya
for the Africa Summit

27:23.375 --> 27:25.778
because we brought the most
amount of private jets.

27:25.812 --> 27:27.546
You understand?
This is their mentality.

27:27.579 --> 27:29.048
They are all elitists, you know.

27:29.081 --> 27:30.750
They have yards, you know,
in the country

27:30.783 --> 27:34.653
where 90% live on...
Live in poverty.

27:34.687 --> 27:36.255
It's self-esteem.

27:36.288 --> 27:37.556
- Self-esteem?
- Yes.

27:39.225 --> 27:40.853
- There's something to that.
- No, I don't think

27:40.860 --> 27:42.494
that self-esteem is about
what you can buy.

27:42.528 --> 27:43.963
Excuse me,
that's not what I said.

27:43.996 --> 27:46.032
As much as Nigeria is bad,

27:46.065 --> 27:48.901
there is...

27:48.935 --> 27:50.102
hope.

27:50.136 --> 27:51.804
♪ On the weapon
of the future ♪

27:51.838 --> 27:53.539
When I grew up, we were like...

27:53.572 --> 27:55.174
We couldn't sit here like this.

27:55.207 --> 27:57.209
The police would come here
and beat everybody up.

27:57.243 --> 27:59.545
A generation will come where
they will say enough is enough.

27:59.578 --> 28:01.981
Let's take back our lives.

28:02.014 --> 28:03.549
Femi Kuti for President.

28:03.582 --> 28:04.851
Don't listen to him.

28:04.884 --> 28:07.286
FKFP, Niger resistance.

28:08.988 --> 28:10.415
♪ Drop the sound on the weapon
of the future ♪

28:10.422 --> 28:12.324
♪

28:12.358 --> 28:14.727
♪ Drop the sound on the weapon
of the future ♪

28:14.761 --> 28:16.929
♪

28:16.963 --> 28:20.066
It is the melody
of the angels of death.

28:20.099 --> 28:22.802
Do not be afraid.

28:34.546 --> 28:35.046
♪

28:43.089 --> 28:45.191
♪

28:45.224 --> 28:48.895
The Hausa are the largest
tribal group in Nigeria.

28:48.928 --> 28:51.297
Known originally as cattlemen,

28:51.330 --> 28:54.266
they have become powerful
politically as well.

29:03.475 --> 29:05.577
♪

29:05.611 --> 29:07.914
This is Dambe boxing,

29:07.947 --> 29:11.083
a very old and very brutal
fighting art

29:11.117 --> 29:13.986
deeply ingrained
in Hausa traditions,

29:14.020 --> 29:16.422
particularly among
the butcher class.

29:19.525 --> 29:22.494
It is a way for tough young men
to earn a few bucks...

29:22.528 --> 29:24.997
♪

29:25.031 --> 29:27.433
We are African men!

29:27.466 --> 29:30.302
Prove themselves,
and break up the grim routine

29:30.336 --> 29:31.670
of their daily lives.

29:31.703 --> 29:32.203
♪

29:39.711 --> 29:41.713
All Hausa versus Hausa.

29:41.747 --> 29:43.382
Yeah, Hausa versus Hausa.

29:43.415 --> 29:46.652
♪

29:46.685 --> 29:48.955
You hit with one hand.

29:48.988 --> 29:51.924
Yeah, and the other one
is to block.

29:54.493 --> 29:56.628
♪

30:00.632 --> 30:03.702
Ooh!

30:03.735 --> 30:04.736
Oh!

30:04.770 --> 30:05.270
♪

30:51.550 --> 30:53.419
Thank you.

30:53.452 --> 30:56.022
Interreligious
and intertribal violence

30:56.055 --> 30:59.992
has been a fact of life
for years in Nigeria.

31:00.026 --> 31:02.128
There are over 300 tribes

31:02.161 --> 31:05.131
and tens of thousands have died
during such conflicts.

31:07.166 --> 31:09.568
In Lagos, some are trying to
rewrite that narrative.

31:14.006 --> 31:16.308
The neighborhood of Agege is a
melting pot

31:16.342 --> 31:18.310
of different tribes
and religious groups.

31:18.344 --> 31:20.913
This was originally
a Yoruba area, yes?

31:20.947 --> 31:22.481
Yes, yes.

31:22.514 --> 31:24.183
But the Hausa people
have been living here

31:24.216 --> 31:26.018
for a very, very long time
cooperating...

31:26.052 --> 31:27.987
Yes, for a long time.
54 years ago.

31:28.020 --> 31:31.157
The intermarriages
in between us and them,

31:31.190 --> 31:35.627
so that is what we... there
are a lot of understanding.

31:35.661 --> 31:38.164
♪

31:38.197 --> 31:41.433
Masa, rice cakes made from
Nigerian sticky rice,

31:41.467 --> 31:42.935
sugar, and potash,

31:42.969 --> 31:44.703
a mineral-rich salt.

31:44.736 --> 31:46.272
This is fura.

31:46.305 --> 31:50.142
It's made from millet and milk.

31:50.176 --> 31:52.244
It's more like a yogurt,
slightly sour.

31:52.278 --> 31:53.812
- Yes.
- Oh, that's great.

31:53.845 --> 31:55.140
This is one of
the surprising foods

31:55.147 --> 31:57.249
that's also made of beans.

31:57.283 --> 31:59.551
- This is all beans?
- Yes.

31:59.585 --> 32:02.721
Danwake, high-protein
bean-flour dumplings

32:02.754 --> 32:06.025
served with tomatoes, onions,
and a peppery sauce.

32:06.058 --> 32:07.726
Mm, delicious.

32:07.759 --> 32:08.827
Moringa.

32:08.860 --> 32:10.429
And Moringa salad,

32:10.462 --> 32:12.364
made from the leaves
of the zogale tree

32:12.398 --> 32:14.700
and said to have
medicinal properties.

32:14.733 --> 32:17.269
Kuli kuli powder is
a garnish or condiment

32:17.303 --> 32:19.405
made from ground peanuts.

32:19.438 --> 32:22.308
What do you see the future
of this area

32:22.341 --> 32:24.010
and your people?

32:24.043 --> 32:26.112
Anything relies on education.

32:26.145 --> 32:31.017
We promote both western
and Arabic knowledge.

32:31.050 --> 32:33.052
The whole Africa,
even the whole world,

32:33.085 --> 32:35.021
is represented in Lagos,

32:35.054 --> 32:37.223
so we have to work together.

32:37.256 --> 32:39.025
The prophet of Islam,
Muhammad...

32:39.058 --> 32:40.559
Sallallahu Alayhi Wa Sallam.

32:40.592 --> 32:43.695
He lived with crystals
and jewels peacefully

32:43.729 --> 32:45.197
without any problem.

32:45.231 --> 32:46.932
We believe if there is no peace,

32:46.965 --> 32:48.434
there will be no progress.

32:48.467 --> 32:51.070
You cannot go to mosque,
you cannot go to church,

32:51.103 --> 32:53.139
you cannot got to school,
you cannot go to wake.

32:53.172 --> 32:56.208
We love Lagos.
We love peace.

32:56.242 --> 32:58.877
And we pray to almighty Allah
to continue living in peace.

32:58.910 --> 33:01.080
God bless Lagos.

33:01.113 --> 33:03.415
God bless Nigeria.

33:06.452 --> 33:06.952
♪

33:19.498 --> 33:19.998
♪

33:30.642 --> 33:31.142
♪

33:41.187 --> 33:44.523
Good cooking takes time.

33:44.556 --> 33:47.326
♪

33:47.359 --> 33:50.028
As more and more
Lagosian men and women

33:50.062 --> 33:51.497
enter the workforce,

33:51.530 --> 33:55.434
fewer and fewer
cook the old way,

33:55.467 --> 33:59.538
long low and slow preparations
that can take hours.

33:59.571 --> 34:03.242
♪

34:03.275 --> 34:05.444
The Lagos upbeat style

34:05.477 --> 34:08.080
makes it impossible for you to
cook everything at home,

34:08.114 --> 34:09.848
so you go, you buy it
from the streets.

34:09.880 --> 34:10.380
♪

34:14.953 --> 34:17.022
So who blogs about food here?

34:17.054 --> 34:18.350
- We all do.
- We all blog about it.

34:18.357 --> 34:20.058
- All of you.
- Yeah.

34:20.092 --> 34:22.628
Ateem, her mom, Iku,
and friend, Oz,

34:22.661 --> 34:24.263
are all hard workers,

34:24.295 --> 34:26.498
holding down multiple jobs
between them,

34:26.532 --> 34:29.467
but they hang on to
their fierce love of food

34:29.501 --> 34:30.702
and cooking.

34:30.735 --> 34:32.338
Who are your readers?

34:32.371 --> 34:34.199
- Primarily Nigerians.
- Homesick Nigerians also,

34:34.206 --> 34:35.706
- I would think, in the states.
- Yes.

34:35.741 --> 34:37.309
Particularly homesick.

34:37.342 --> 34:39.112
But then people that are
married to Nigerians

34:39.145 --> 34:41.746
that want to learn the cuisine.
Ahh.

34:41.780 --> 34:44.616
These days,
one often eats quickly

34:44.650 --> 34:46.351
at a place like this,

34:46.385 --> 34:49.521
Yakoyo, serving traditional
Nigerian dishes

